{"key":"processedPost-13740706","value":{"id":13740706,"first":13737786,"last":13750882,"when":1294339324,"utime":"01/06/11 08:42 PM","content":"Correct, rhizomorphic mycelium is vastly over rated.&nbsp; It's something we tend to isolate in species which form it, but there's no guarantee that a perfectly rhizomorphic mycelium on a petri dish will remain that way when it goes to grains, or that it will be a particularly good fruiter.&nbsp; It's related far more to nutrient load than genetics, with a nutrient poor substrate more likely to develop rhizomorphs.<br />When doing strain isolation, it's important to grab enough strains so that you can test them all to find a good fruiting strain.&nbsp; When growers isolate a single rhizomorphic strain and then toss out all the others, they rarely end up with a good one.<br />RR","title":"Re: ?Rhizo Q?"}}